Adding a progress bar or some form of feedback during the file upload process can greatly enhance the user experience by providing visual cues about the upload status. Axios makes this manageable by allowing you to hook into the upload progress events.

Here’s how you can implement this feature using Axios’ `onUploadProgress` in a React component:

### Step 1: Setup State for Progress

First, you need a piece of state to keep track of the upload progress:

```javascript
const [uploadProgress, setUploadProgress] = useState(0);
```

### Step 2: Implement the Upload Function with Progress Tracking

When uploading files with Axios and tracking the progress, you can use the `onUploadProgress` event. This event gives you access to the `ProgressEvent`, from which you can calculate the percentage of the upload that has been completed.

Here’s how you can adjust your `valid` function to include upload progress tracking:

```javascript
async function valid() {
    try {
        const formData = new FormData();
        if (Video) {
            formData.append('video', Video);
        }
        Images.forEach(image => {
            formData.append('images', image);
        });
        formData.append('data', JSON.stringify({
            "categorie": Categorie,
            "plusCategorie": plusCategorie,
            "ville": Ville,
            "secteur": Secteur,
            "NumeroTele": Telephone,
            "Etat": Etat,
            "Prix": Prix,
            "titre": Titre,
            "TexteAnnonce": TexteAnnonce,
        }));

        const response = await axios.post('http://127.0.0.1:5000/add', formData, {
            onUploadProgress: progressEvent => {
                const percentCompleted = Math.round((progressEvent.loaded * 100) / progressEvent.total);
                setUploadProgress(percentCompleted);
            }
        });

        console.log('Response:', response);
        window.location.replace('http://127.0.0.1:3000/');
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error fetching data:', error);
        alert('An error occurred while uploading. Please try again.');
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Displaying Progress in UI

With the upload progress now being tracked and stored in your component’s state, you can display this progress to the user. A simple way is to use an HTML `<progress>` element:

```javascript
<progress value={uploadProgress} max="100"></progress>
```

Or you could create a more visually appealing progress bar using a library like Bootstrap or implement your custom styled progress bar.

### Example with a Custom Progress Bar

If you're styling your progress bar, you might have something like this in your JSX:

```javascript
<div className="progress-bar">
    <div className="progress-bar-fill" style={{width: `${uploadProgress}%`}}></div>
    <span className="progress-bar-text">{uploadProgress}%</span>
</div>
```

And accompanying CSS could be something like:

```css
.progress-bar {
    width: 100%;
    background-color: #e0e0e0;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 3px;
}

.progress-bar-fill {
    height: 20px;
    background-color: blue;
    width: 0%;
    border-radius: 5px;
    text-align: center;
    transition: width 0.5s ease-in-out;
}

.progress-bar-text {
    position: absolute;
    display: inline-block;
    width: 100%;
    color: white;
    font-weight: bold;
}
```

This will create a simple progress bar that fills up horizontally as the upload progresses and displays the percentage of completion.

Integrating a progress feedback mechanism like this will significantly enhance the file upload feature's user experience in your application.

The issue you're encountering with the video upload is rooted in how you're attempting to set the video file from the input field in your React component. Specifically, the line `setVideo(e.target.value)` attempts to assign the input's value attribute (which would just be a filename as a string, not the file object itself) to your video state. For file uploads, you need the actual file object, not just its value attribute. This is why you aren't successfully uploading the video file.

Here's how you can correct the issue:

### Fixing the Video Upload

Assuming `setVideo` is a useState setter function meant to store the video file in your component's state, you should change the input's onChange handler to pass the file object, not its value string:

```jsx
<input
  id="videoUpload"
  accept="video/*"
  className="form-control form-control-lg"
  type="file"
  onChange={(e) => {
    if (e.target.files.length > 0) {
      setVideo(e.target.files[0]); // Set the first (and presumably only) file object
    }
  }}
/>
```

In this corrected version, `e.target.files[0]` retrieves the first file object from the input (since you're expecting a single video file). This way, the actual file object is stored in your component's state, ready to be included in the FormData object when making an API request to upload the video.

